<paragraph blockId="27.[136,1452,158,1445]" pageId="27" pageNumber="180">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[189,444,806,832]" pageId="27" pageNumber="180">Conservation Status:</emphasis>
<emphasis box="[444,469,807,832]" italics="true" pageId="27" pageNumber="180">—</emphasis>
The species has been collected only twice at the same locality, a private property in the municipality of Guaratinga. 
<taxonomicName box="[507,731,842,868]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Melastomataceae" genus="Bertolonia" kingdom="Plantae" order="Myrtales" pageId="27" pageNumber="180" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="violacea">
<emphasis box="[507,731,842,868]" italics="true" pageId="27" pageNumber="180">Bertolonia violacea</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
has an AOO of 
<quantity box="[927,989,842,871]" metricMagnitude="3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="4.0" pageId="27" pageNumber="180" unit="km" value="4.0">4 km</quantity>
², and should be classified as “Critically Endangered” (CR), following 
<bibRefCitation author="IUCN Standards and Petitions Subcommittee &amp; Cambridge, UK" box="[476,627,878,904]" pageId="27" pageNumber="180" refId="ref19879" refString="IUCN Standards and Petitions Subcommittee (2017) Guidelines for Using the IUCN Red List Categories and Criteria. Version 13 (March 2017). Prepared by the IUCN species survival commission. IUCN Council, Gland, Switzerland and Cambridge, UK, 108 pp. Available from: http: // cmsdocs. s 3. amazonaws. com / RedList Guidelines. pdf (Accessed 9 February 2019)" type="book" year="2017">IUCN (2017)</bibRefCitation>
categories. It occurs only in one locality, so it is not possible to calculate its Extent of Occurrence (EOO).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="27" pageNumber="180" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="27.[136,1452,158,1445]" pageId="27" pageNumber="180">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[189,265,950,976]" pageId="27" pageNumber="180">Notes:</emphasis>
— 
<taxonomicName box="[294,515,950,976]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Melastomataceae" genus="Bertolonia" kingdom="Plantae" order="Myrtales" pageId="27" pageNumber="180" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="violacea">
<emphasis box="[294,515,950,976]" italics="true" pageId="27" pageNumber="180">Bertolonia violacea</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is endemic to 
<collectingRegion box="[677,745,950,976]" country="Brazil" name="Bahia" pageId="27" pageNumber="180">Bahia</collectingRegion>
, occurring in lowland forest (
<figureCitation box="[1073,1167,950,977]" captionStart="FIGURE 13" captionStartId="19.[136,229,1730,1752]" captionTargetBox="[346,1239,435,1693]" captionTargetId="figure-140@19.[340,1247,425,1706]" captionTargetPageId="19" captionText="FIGURE 13. Distributions of species of Bertolonia in Bahia.A.Bertolonia linearifolia. B. Bertolonia maculata. C. Bertolonia marmorata. D. Bertolonia reginatoi. E. Bertolonia riocontensis. F. Bertolonia violacea. G. Bertolonia vitoriana." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6597718" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6597718/files/figure.png" pageId="27" pageNumber="180">Fig. 13f</figureCitation>
). It has been cultivated in a greenhouse at the “Museu de Biologia Mello Leitão” in the state of 
<collectingRegion box="[922,1082,986,1012]" country="Brazil" name="Espirito Santo" pageId="27" pageNumber="180">Espírito Santo</collectingRegion>
where it got spread, weedy-like. Collected with flowers and fruits in April to May. 
<taxonomicName box="[721,946,1022,1048]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Melastomataceae" genus="Bertolonia" kingdom="Plantae" order="Myrtales" pageId="27" pageNumber="180" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="violacea">
<emphasis box="[721,946,1022,1048]" italics="true" pageId="27" pageNumber="180">Bertolonia violacea</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is characterized by the remarkable purplish indumentum covering the plants. It has one of the smallest leaves in the genus (about 
<quantity box="[1089,1193,1058,1085]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="4.75" metricValueMax="7.0" metricValueMin="2.5" pageId="27" pageNumber="180" unit="cm" value="4.75" valueMax="7.0" valueMin="2.5">2.5–7 cm</quantity>
long), together with 
<taxonomicName class="Magnoliopsida" family="Melastomataceae" genus="Bertolonia" kingdom="Plantae" order="Myrtales" pageId="27" pageNumber="180" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="alternifolia">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="27" pageNumber="180">B. alternifolia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, 
<emphasis box="[275,465,1094,1120]" italics="true" pageId="27" pageNumber="180">
<taxonomicName box="[275,460,1094,1120]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Melastomataceae" genus="Bertolonia" kingdom="Plantae" order="Myrtales" pageId="27" pageNumber="180" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="angustipetala">B. angustipetala</taxonomicName>
,
</emphasis>
and 
<taxonomicName box="[517,668,1094,1120]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Melastomataceae" genus="Bertolonia" kingdom="Plantae" order="Myrtales" pageId="27" pageNumber="180" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="kollmannii">
<emphasis box="[517,668,1094,1120]" italics="true" pageId="27" pageNumber="180">B. kollmannii</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. 
<taxonomicName box="[680,901,1094,1120]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Melastomataceae" genus="Bertolonia" kingdom="Plantae" order="Myrtales" pageId="27" pageNumber="180" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="violacea">
<emphasis box="[680,901,1094,1120]" italics="true" pageId="27" pageNumber="180">Bertolonia violacea</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is similar to 
<emphasis box="[1044,1209,1095,1120]" italics="true" pageId="27" pageNumber="180">
<taxonomicName authorityName="Naudin" authorityYear="1851" baseAuthorityName="Naudin" baseAuthorityYear="1848" box="[1044,1202,1095,1120]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Melastomataceae" genus="Bertolonia" kingdom="Plantae" order="Myrtales" pageId="27" pageNumber="180" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="marmorata">B. marmorata</taxonomicName>
;
</emphasis>
they share the widely elliptic or widely ovate leaf blades, and also the branches, leaf blades, hypanthium and sepals glandulose-punctate (trichomes less than 
<quantity box="[367,454,1166,1193]" metricMagnitude="-4" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.0" pageId="27" pageNumber="180" unit="mm" value="0.1">0.1 mm</quantity>
long) and glandulose-villose or glandulose-pilose (trichomes 
<quantity box="[1149,1263,1166,1193]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.75" metricValueMax="2.5" metricValueMin="1.0" pageId="27" pageNumber="180" unit="mm" value="1.75" valueMax="2.5" valueMin="1.0">1–2.5 mm</quantity>
long). However, 
<taxonomicName box="[136,357,1202,1228]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Melastomataceae" genus="Bertolonia" kingdom="Plantae" order="Myrtales" pageId="27" pageNumber="180" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="violacea">
<emphasis box="[136,357,1202,1228]" italics="true" pageId="27" pageNumber="180">Bertolonia violacea</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
differs by the leaves with an acute apex and revolute margins (
<emphasis box="[1053,1083,1203,1228]" italics="true" pageId="27" pageNumber="180">vs.</emphasis>
rounded apex and entire margins in 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Naudin" authorityYear="1851" baseAuthorityName="Naudin" baseAuthorityYear="1848" box="[166,323,1239,1264]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Melastomataceae" genus="Bertolonia" kingdom="Plantae" order="Myrtales" pageId="27" pageNumber="180" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="marmorata">
<emphasis box="[166,323,1239,1264]" italics="true" pageId="27" pageNumber="180">B. marmorata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
), the purplish color of the leaf trichomes (
<emphasis box="[804,835,1239,1264]" italics="true" pageId="27" pageNumber="180">vs.</emphasis>
brownish in 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Naudin" authorityYear="1851" baseAuthorityName="Naudin" baseAuthorityYear="1848" box="[984,1141,1239,1264]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Melastomataceae" genus="Bertolonia" kingdom="Plantae" order="Myrtales" pageId="27" pageNumber="180" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="marmorata">
<emphasis box="[984,1141,1239,1264]" italics="true" pageId="27" pageNumber="180">B. marmorata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
), and the anthers dehiscing through an extrorse pore (
<emphasis box="[427,457,1275,1300]" italics="true" pageId="27" pageNumber="180">vs.</emphasis>
introrse in 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Naudin" authorityYear="1851" baseAuthorityName="Naudin" baseAuthorityYear="1848" box="[585,743,1275,1300]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Melastomataceae" genus="Bertolonia" kingdom="Plantae" order="Myrtales" pageId="27" pageNumber="180" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="marmorata">
<emphasis box="[585,743,1275,1300]" italics="true" pageId="27" pageNumber="180">B. marmorata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
). For more details see 
<bibRefCitation author="Bisewski, G. C. A. &amp; Bacci, L. &amp; Amorim, A. M. A. &amp; Goldenberg, R." box="[999,1247,1274,1300]" pageId="27" pageNumber="180" pagination="563 - 574" refId="ref18940" refString="Bisewski, G. C. A., Bacci, L. F, Amorim, A. M. A. &amp; Goldenberg, R. (2020) Novelties in Bertolonia (Melastomataceae) from northeastern Brazil. Brazilian Journal of Botany 43 (3): 563 - 574. https: // doi. org / 10.1007 / s 40415 - 020 - 00630 - 7" type="journal article" year="2020">
Bisewski 
<emphasis box="[1109,1165,1274,1300]" italics="true" pageId="27" pageNumber="180">et al.</emphasis>
(2020)
</bibRefCitation>
and 
<tableCitation box="[1300,1384,1274,1300]" captionStart="TABLE 1" captionStartId="6.[136,224,623,649]" captionTargetPageId="6" captionText="TABLE 1. Selected morphological characters scored for species in Bertolonia that occur in the state of Bahia, Brazil. “GP”= Glandulose-punctate; “GV”= Glandulose-villose." httpUri="http://table.plazi.org/id/DF76660492567734FF76FDBFF843BEC2" pageId="27" pageNumber="180" tableUuid="DF76660492567734FF76FDBFF843BEC2">Table 1</tableCitation>
.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="27.[136,1452,158,1445]" pageId="27" pageNumber="180">
The original description of 
<taxonomicName box="[497,624,1310,1336]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Melastomataceae" genus="Bertolonia" kingdom="Plantae" order="Myrtales" pageId="27" pageNumber="180" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="violacea">
<emphasis box="[497,624,1310,1336]" italics="true" pageId="27" pageNumber="180">B. violacea</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
indicated the 
<typeStatus box="[783,881,1310,1336]" pageId="27" pageNumber="180">holotype</typeStatus>
(
<taxonomicName box="[896,988,1310,1336]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Asteraceae" genus="Fontana" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Plantae" order="Asterales" pageId="27" pageNumber="180" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="genus">Fontana</taxonomicName>
5909) deposited at MBML, but there are two duplicates in this herbarium with different catalogue numbers. To solve this problem, we decided to choose one of them as the 
<typeStatus box="[309,412,1382,1408]" pageId="27" pageNumber="180">lectotype</typeStatus>
of the species. In this case, the specimen with an online photo available was selected (see http://splink.cria.org.br/ and http://reflora.jbrj.gov.br /reflora/).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
